We recommended that the BAC, end-user and other concerned officials:

a.	continue to require updated file of its supplier to facilitate identification of legally, technically, and financially capable supplier and contractor in case of alternative modes of procurement especially during emergency;

b.	require submission of correct and appropriate OSS which contains complete declarations/ commitments as prescribed in RA 9184 and other GPPB issuances, as applicable, for every procurement project that requires the same;

c.	clearly indicate in the RFQ/Proposal at what stage the documentary requirements shall be submitted when alternative mode of procurement is used;

d.	ensure that NOA, PO/Contract and NTP, if necessary, are posted in PhilGEPS/GPPB Online Portal or any other online platforms that may be required for the purpose and likewise attach any proof of posting of the same to the LGU’s website and conspicuous places within the Municipality; and

e.	explain the absence of target date of completion/implementation in the POWs/PR of the subject procurement projects and provide justification on the grant of 60-day extension in the delivery of supplies, furniture and fixtures considering that the procurement was based on urgent situations.

We recommended that the:

a.	Inventory Committee conduct a complete physical count of all the properties and prepare properly the (i) RPCPPE indicating each property item rather than lump sum balances per account to establish the actual quantity counted and (ii) RPCLRN presenting the local road network by road and its component; 

b.	MGSO prepare and maintain appropriate property cards for all the properties, including all roads and its components; 

c.	Municipal Engineer provide the Municipal Accountant and MGSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components especially those that were consolidated in RLRN without the necessary details and description;

d.	MGSO, Municipal Engineer and Municipal Accountant exert efforts in the reconciliation of RLRN and the accounting records; and

e.	Municipal Accountant (i) include in the Notes to Financial Statements the required disclosure for Road Networks, and (ii) coordinate with Municipal Treasurer, MGSO and Municipal Assessor in gathering necessary documents relative to the unrecorded parcels of land and recognize the same in the books at cost or fair value as appropriate.

We recommended that the:

a.	BAC Chairperson, thru the BAC Technical Working Group and Secretariat, provide valid explanation on the noted lapses specifically on the delays in the procurement process, inconsistencies in the dates indicated in various documents and the absence of necessary procurement documents;

b.	BAC strictly observe the period of action provided in RA 9184 and its IRR within which certain stages of the procurement process must be completed;

c.	BAC and Municipal Engineer properly evaluate and ensure consistency in the dates indicated in all the relevant documents submitted pertaining to procurement and implementation of contracts, especially the start and completion date, for proper and accurate evaluation of contract implementation; and

d.	Municipal Accountant, BAC, and Municipal Engineer ensure that future claims be supported with the documents as prescribed under COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012.

We recommended that the: 

a.	MPDC, MDRRMC and MDRRM Officer provide the specific and detailed PPAs in the LDRRMFIP to facilitate implementation of the disaster prevention, mitigation and preparedness activities and to avoid the use of fund of these PPAs to augment the insufficiency of funds of some PPAs without undergoing proper budgeting procedures.  Likewise, the MDRRM Office ensure that the amount appropriated for the PPAs shall be the ceiling amount in the preparation of the project design;

b.	MDRRMC use the prescribed form shown in Annex A of COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012 in preparing the Annual and Supplemental/Revised LDRRMFIP;

c.	MDRRMC revisit the conditions on the grant of financial assistance by LBP specifically the return of unutilized amount, if any, and coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant for the immediate return of the ₱25,000.00 to the LBP, if stipulated, or for its remittance to the BTr;

d.	MDRRMC prepare Revised/Supplemental LDRRMFIP whenever there are new PPAs that will be implemented out of the MDRRMF and to observe strict compliance with Section 6.2 of the NDRRMC-DBM-DILG Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-1 dated March 25, 2013; and

e.	Municipal Accountant and Municipal Budget Officer reconcile their records pertaining to the utilization of MDRRMF before transferring the unexpended balance to Special Trust Fund at the end of the year to ensure that all the unutilized balance of QRF and 70% MF- MOOE of MDRRMF will be transferred correctly.

We recommended that the:

a.	MDRRM Officer, MGSO and the Municipal Accountant submit written explanation on the procurement of diesel more than the project requirement which was equivalent to ₱186,832.00 payment out of the MDRRMF;

b.	BAC and MGSO ensure that the quantity of fuel being procured matches the project requirements per POW and PR;

c.	BAC justify the existence and the veracity of the ground relied for the use of Negotiated Procurement (Emergency Cases) for the procurement of modular tent; otherwise, explain how the use of such modality, instead of competitive bidding, has not been detrimental to the government;

d.	BAC and end-user or procuring unit comply with the requirements of GPPB Resolution No. 03-2020 in case Negotiated Procurement (Emergency Procurement) will be resorted to as procurement modality; 

e.	Municipal Treasurer secure Acknowledgment Receipt from the two recipients of cash assistance claimed to have not signed the original distribution list as a substantial evidence that they had received their claims and henceforth, require the submission of authority from the claimant and identification documents whenever payments are made to individual other that the payee; and

f.	MDRRM Officer and Municipal Accountant refrain from paying expenses through cash advance if it is practical to pay the supplier/contractor directly by check.

We recommended that the:

a.	BAC (i) send invitations to observers at least five (5) calendar days before the date of the procurement stage/activity, (ii) notify the losing bidder within three (3) days from the issuance of the resolution recommending award of the contract, (iii) post the NOA in the PhilGEPS within three (3) calendar days from its issuance and in any conspicuous place in the premises of the Municipality, (iv) ensure that the date of receipt of NOA and NTP were specified, and (v) use the latest GPPB-prescribed PBD, all in compliance to the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184;

b.	TWG carefully examine the documents submitted by the Lowest Calculated Bidder during post-qualification in compliance to Section 34.3 of the Revised IRR of RA 9184;

c.	Municipal Accountant ensure that advance payment to the winning bidder is supported with an irrevocable letter of credit, bank guarantee or a surety bond callable upon demand as required under Item 4.2 in Annex E of the Revised IRR of RA 9184; and

d.	Henceforth, the Municipal Mayor, through concerned officials, ensure compliance with the guidelines covering the utilization of the funds received from DILG and other National Government Agencies, if any.

Based on the foregoing, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor, through the Municipal Accountant and other concerned officials to:

a.	strictly monitor officers and employees with outstanding cash advances and refrain from granting additional cash advance to an employee prior to settlement of his/her previous cash advances;

b.	grant cash advance for travelling expenses directly to the officers and employees who will be travelling to establish accountability;

c.	consider designating other bonded employees as Special Disbursing Officers to cash advance for special purpose/undertaking, whenever necessary, to avoid overlapping cash advances;

d.	ensure that liquidation of the accountable officers are within the reglementary period timely in compliance to the prescribed guidelines  COA Circular Nos. 97-002, 2012-001 and 2012-004, as applicable;

e.	pay by check directly to the supplier whenever practicable in accordance with the general principle of imprest system; and

f.	ensure that the utilization of cash advances were supported by proper and sufficient supporting documents.

We recommended that the GAD Focal Point System, and other offices concerned:

a.	ensure that, in the preparation of GPB, GAD objectives are SMART (specific, measurable, attainable, realistic and time-bound), reflect the results that the Municipality intends to achieve, and not articulated as an activity statement;

b.	comply with RA No. 9184 and its Revised IRR and other existing regulations in the implementation of the PPAs included in the GPB; 

c.	consistently observe the guide in completing the GAD AR prescribed under PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC 2016-01, especially in accomplishing Columns 7, 8, 12 and 14;

d.	exhaust all available resources for the collection and processing of complete and reliable data requirements of the GAD Database to be used in data processing and gender analysis for gender-responsive planning and budgeting; 

e.	include priority gender issues in the succeeding GPB that may be identified through analysis of the information in the GAD database as well as the corresponding PPAs that will address the same;

f.	prepare the GAD Agenda through proper consultations with local functionaries and stakeholders to ensure that priority gender issues will be addressed within the timeframe; and 

g.	make representation with the Sangguniang Bayan to consider amending its existing GAD Code to include provision for the development of IRR indicating among others the groups and entities which shall promulgate the same.

We recommended that the:

Municipal Accountant and GSO coordinate and prepare supporting schedules to facilitate the proper reconciliation of the property accounts and establishment of actual existence, ownership and condition of the properties, and prepare and maintain appropriate property records and reports for PPE account; 

GSO prepare and maintain RLRN and Road Map to account for the Local Roads and reconcile with the Registry of Public Infrastructures maintained by the Accounting Office, and exert efforts to have the pieces of land owned by the Municipal Government titled in its name;

Inventory Committee conduct a complete physical count and technical valuation of the local road network to determine the current value of the road components to facilitate the preparation of the RPCLRN;

Municipal Engineer to maintain road map and provide the Municipal Accountant and the GSO with complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects; and

Municipal Budget Officer to propose the appropriation of funds on a per parcel basis to ensure that the Municipality’s Budget can accommodate the survey and titling of each land in the name of the Municipality to preserve legal rights over their real properties and to avoid exposure to adverse third-party claims.

We recommended that the:

BAC Chairman through the BAC Secretariat: 
(i)	submit the documents to support variation order as per Item 1.5.a of Annex E of the Revised IRR of RA 9184;
(ii)	provide explanation on the delay in the posting of NOA and NTP in PhilGEPS and ensure compliance with Section Section 37.1.6 and 37.4.2 of the Revised IRR of RA 9184 in posting the NOA and NTP in PhilGEPS; and
(iii)	provide justification on the noted discrepancies between items indicated in POW and actual items procured, handwritten dates in the contract agreement, and in the contract duration;

BAC and Municipal Engineer properly evaluate and ensure the correctness in the dates indicated in the supporting documents submitted, particularly the start and completion date for proper and accurate evaluation of contract implementation;

Municipal Accountant abide with Annex E of the Revised IRR of RA 9184 in the proper treatment of advance payment;

Municipal Engineer ensure that the statement of time elapsed is prepared for every project so that the details regarding the implementation of the project could be determined; and

Municipal Development Council together with Budget Officer and Municipal Engineer evaluate the actual condition of projects implemented and appropriate sufficient funds, if needed, for the maintenance of the projects in order that the projects may be use for its intended purpose.

We recommended that Municipal Mayor instruct the:

Municipal Engineer provide acceptable justification in the grant of suspension of work for the Construction of Evacuation Center at Barangay Melgar A and Concreting of Road at Sitio Tabag, Aliso, Centro B. Barangay Metolza, and ensure that statement of time elapsed is prepared for every project so that the details regarding the implementation of the project could be determined;

